{{!-- see google docs, handlebars.js, partial templates --}}
{{!-- partial template used in homepage.handlebars --}}
<article class="post">
  <div class="title">
      {{!-- when we pass an object to the partial template we are actually just passing
      the objects properties. So just use the property names and not dot notation
      like, ex. post.title --}}
    <a href="{{post_url}}" target="_blank">{{title}}</a>
    {{!-- see below comment for custom helper functions --}}
    <span>({{format_url post_url}})</span>
  </div>
  <div class="meta">
      {{!-- Now all we have to do to use our custom helper functions in the templates is add 
        them to the Handlebars.js expressions.
        This works essentially the same way as calling format_date(created_at). 
        initialized these helpers to work in server.js --}}
    {{vote_count}} {{format_plural "point" vote_count}} by {{user.username}} on {{format_date created_at}}
    |
    {{!-- The last helper, format_plural, takes two arguments, 
    We're not using () to pass arguments, so we can separate arguments with spaces. 
    This works essentially the same way as calling format_plural("comment", comments.length) --}}
    <a href="/post/{{id}}">{{comments.length}} {{format_plural "comment" comments.length}}</a>
  </div>
</article>